      "content": "Early 20th-century eugenicists, particularly in the United States, relied heavily on pseudo-scientific theories to justify their racist ideologies. They argued that certain racial groups, such as whites, were inherently superior to others due to their perceived genetic superiority, as exemplified by the concept of the \"Nordic\" ideal. They claimed that this superiority was reflected in physical characteristics, intelligence, and moral values, and that it was the duty of society to preserve and promote this genetic elite through selective breeding and sterilization. They also used the \"survival of the fittest\" concept, adapted from Charles Darwin's theory of evolution, to justify the idea that the strongest and most capable individuals should reproduce, while those deemed \"inferior\" should be prevented from having children.",
